A good loop therefore needs four explicit stop rules: goal reached, budget exhausted, risk threshold exceeded, or human rejection. Both vendors provide building blocks for this: OpenAI through guardrails, human review, tracing, approvals, background/state handling, and sandboxed runtime controls; Anthropic through tool-use stop reasons, permission modes, prompt-injection defenses, auto-mode classifiers, rate/spend limits, and managed-agent infrastructure. 

Platform differences that should change your loop design
OpenAI Codex is explicitly a coding agent: it can read, edit, and run code locally or in cloud environments, uses repo-scoped instruction files such as AGENTS.md, supports sandbox/approval presets, and is tuned for long-running coding work with compaction and prompt-caching optimization. OpenAI’s own guidance recommends Codex-tuned models for agentic coding and suggests medium reasoning effort as the default interactive balance, reserving higher effort for harder, longer-horizon work. This makes OpenAI especially strong for loops whose unit of progress is a patch, test result, or pull request. 

Anthropic Claude is a broader assistant platform with two distinct operating modes: direct model access through the Messages API, where your application executes client-side tools after stop_reason: "tool_use", and managed or semi-managed harnesses through Claude Managed Agents or Claude Code, where runtime, permissions, and telemetry are more platform-provided. Anthropic recommends the most capable Opus-tier models for complex ambiguous tool use, faster Haiku models for straightforward work, and typically medium effort as the default starting point for agentic coding on Sonnet-class models, with higher effort for harder autonomous tasks. This makes Claude particularly strong when you want flexible tool orchestration, rich long-context reasoning, or a clean upgrade path from explicit loops to hosted agent infrastructure. 

The loop-design implication is straightforward. For Codex-like models, prefer longer execution windows, richer repo context, automated test/repair loops, and stronger environment pinning. For Claude-like models, invest more in tool schema design, permission policy, response-format constraints, explicit prompt structure, and a conscious decision between “I own orchestration” and “the vendor owns orchestration.” In both cases, avoid free-form tool interfaces and unbounded browsing or shell access. 

