Across both platforms, the key SDLC shift is that the harness itself becomes part of the product: prompts, tool contracts, validators, approval policies, memory/compaction policy, and telemetry pipelines should be reviewed, tested, and versioned exactly like application code. OpenAI says this explicitly in its “agent improvement loop” material, and Anthropic’s testing guidance likewise treats evaluation as central to iterative prompt and system design. 

Safety, security, governance, and testing
For governance, start with rate limits, spend limits, and explicit approval policies. OpenAI exposes project and organization rate-limit controls, spend alerts, audit logs, and human-review nodes; Anthropic exposes rate/spend limits, workspace-level controls, permission rules, Usage/Cost reporting, and Compliance / Admin APIs. This means the correct control plane is not just “the prompt.” It is a combination of policy, credential scope, runtime permissions, and telemetry. 

On alignment, OpenAI’s production lineage is strongly associated with RLHF, while Anthropic’s Claude stack adds Constitutional AI and a public “constitution.” The practical implication is not that one platform removes the need for safeguards; it is that both support rubric-based critique and policy-driven prompting, but neither should be trusted without external validation, approvals, and auditability. 

For security, design as if prompt injection is unavoidable in principle. OpenAI recommends keeping untrusted text out of developer instructions, constraining downstream flow with structured outputs, enabling tool approvals, and running guardrails and trace graders. Anthropic recommends layered defenses against jailbreaks and prompt injection, and its Claude Code product explicitly warns that permission enforcement is outside the model, not inside it. NCSC and OWASP reinforce the deeper point: current LLMs do not enforce a hard boundary between instructions and data, so teams must rely on containment and blast-radius reduction rather than hoping for a silver bullet. 

For privacy and regulated data, keep retention choices explicit. OpenAI’s Responses API stores application state for 30 days by default unless store=false and/or Zero Data Retention applies; background mode temporarily stores response data to support polling; tracing is unavailable under ZDR. Anthropic offers ZDR and HIPAA-ready arrangements for eligible features, says retained data is not used for training without express permission, and documents that some features are not ZDR-eligible. If you need high-assurance privacy, choose the smallest feature set that remains ZDR-compatible and disable unnecessary tracing or sensitive trace capture. 

For supply-chain risk, treat agent-produced artifacts like any other release artifact: require signed provenance, SBOMs, and policy enforcement in CI. SLSA provides a practical framework for build integrity; Sigstore provides keyless signing and transparency logs; GitHub artifact attestations provide cryptographically signed build provenance. This matters more for agents because the system that writes code may also modify dependencies, workflows, or deployment manifests. 

Testing should cover five layers. Unit tests verify deterministic tool wrappers and validators. Integration tests verify tool-call contracts, permission gates, and artifact generation. Task-evals measure acceptance criteria on real issue distributions. Adversarial / red-team tests probe jailbreaks, prompt injection, data exfiltration, and unsafe tool use. Chaos tests deliberately inject transient API failures, 429s, corrupted tool outputs, stale caches, and partial network loss to ensure the loop degrades safely rather than silently drifting. This structure aligns well with OpenAI’s eval-driven guidance, Anthropic’s success-criteria framework, OpenAI’s red-teaming work, and classic SRE error-budget practice. 

Useful metrics are: task pass rate; patch acceptance / merge rate; unit/integration pass rate; tool success rate; retry-exhaustion rate; 429 rate; p95/p99 latency for model and tool steps; cache-hit rate; cost per successful task; false-positive and false-negative rate for safety gates; human-override rate; and incident/rollback rate. Anthropic’s monitoring docs provide specific metrics and events for sessions, tokens, costs, lines changed, permission decisions, and retry exhaustion; OpenAI provides traces, rate-limit headers, request IDs, and governance dashboards. 

Performance, reproducibility, monitoring, and incident response
Performance tuning is mostly about controlling context growth and choosing the right intelligence tier. OpenAI recommends Codex-tuned models for agentic coding, medium reasoning effort for interactive work, compaction for long-running sessions, and prompt caching to reduce latency and input cost substantially. Anthropic recommends starting complex ambiguous tool work on Opus-class models, using medium effort for agentic coding on Sonnet-class models, enabling prompt caching and cache pre-warming where static prefixes are large, omitting visible thinking when you want lower latency, and using Batch or Priority/Standard service tiers according to SLA needs. 

For reproducibility, version three things together: the exact model identifier or snapshot, the prompt/instruction package, and the evaluation dataset. OpenAI explicitly documents pinned snapshots for consistent behavior and warns that prompting behavior can change between snapshots; Anthropic supports model aliases for convenience but full model names for exact selection, and its release notes provide migration guidance. In practical terms, release every agent change as a tuple such as {model_id, prompt_bundle_hash, tool_schema_hash, eval_set_version, container_digest} and require green evals before promotion. 

